    <!-- <p>It's traditional to use the variable <m>x</m> to represent numbers on the left-right axis, so we call that axis the <term><m>x</m>-axis</term>.<idx><h sortby="x"><m>x</m>-axis</h></idx> For similar reasons we call the down-up axis the <term><m>y</m>-axis</term>.<idx><h sortby="y"><m>y</m>-axis</h></idx> The point <m>(0,0)</m> is where the two axes meet, and we call it the <term>origin</term>.<idx><h>origin</h></idx> We use an <term>ordered pair</term>, like <m>(2,3)</m>, to represent the location of a point.<idx><h>ordered pair</h></idx> We are ready for a formal definition of the <term>Cartesian Coordinate System</term> and several associated vocabulary terms.</p> -->

    <aside>
        <!-- <title>Coordinates <abbr>vs.</abbr> Intervals</title> -->
        <!-- <p>Unfortunately, the way we write ordered pairs looks exactly like the way we write open intervals in interval notation. It's up to you to use <em>context</em> to understand if something like <m>(2,3)</m> is the point <m>2</m> units right of the origin and <m>3</m> units up, or if it's the interval of all numbers between <m>2</m> and <m>3</m>.</p> -->
        <title>Notation Issue: Coordinates or Interval?</title>
        <p>Unfortunately, the notation for an ordered pair looks exactly like interval notation for an open interval. <em>Context</em> will help you understand if <m>(2,3)</m> indicates the point <m>2</m> units right of the origin and <m>3</m> units up, or if <m>(2,3)</m> indicates the interval of all real numbers between <m>2</m> and <m>3</m>.</p>
    </aside>

    <p>Traditionally, the variable <m>x</m> represents numbers on the horizontal axis, so it is called the <term><m>x</m>-axis</term>.<idx><h sortby="x"><m>x</m>-axis</h></idx> The variable <m>y</m> represents numbers on the vertical axis, so it is called the <term><m>y</m>-axis</term>.<idx><h sortby="y"><m>y</m>-axis</h></idx> The axes meet at the point <m>(0,0)</m>, which is called the <term>origin</term>.<idx><h>origin</h></idx> Every point in the plane is represented by an <term>ordered pair</term>, <m>(x,y)</m>.<idx><h>ordered pair</h></idx></p>

    <p>In a Cartesian coordinate system, the map of Carl's neighborhood would look like this:</p>

