    <definition xml:id="definition-cartesian-coordinate-system">
        <title>Cartesian Coordinate System</title>
        <idx><h>Cartesian Coordinate System</h></idx>
        <statement>
            <p>A <url href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cartesian_coordinate_system">Cartesian coordinate system</url><fn><url href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cartesian_coordinate_system">en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cartesian<underscore/>coordinate<underscore/>system</url></fn> is a coordinate system that specifies each point uniquely in a plane by a pair of numerical coordinates, which are the signed (positive/negative) distances to the point from two fixed perpendicular directed lines, measured in the same unit of length. Those two reference lines are called the <term>horizontal axis</term> and <term>vertical axis</term>, and the point where they meet is the <term>origin</term>.<idx><h>axis</h><h>horizontal</h></idx><idx><h>axis</h><h>vertical</h></idx> The horizontal and vertical axes are often called the <term><m>x</m>-axis</term> and <term><m>y</m>-axis</term>.<idx><h sortby="x"><m>x</m>-axis</h></idx><idx><h sortby="y"><m>y</m>-axis</h></idx></p>

            <p>The plane based on the <m>x</m>-axis and <m>y</m>-axis is called a <term>coordinate plane</term>.<idx><h>coordinate plane</h></idx> The ordered pair used to locate a point is called the point's <term>coordinates</term><idx><h>coordinates</h></idx>, which consists of an <term><m>x</m>-coordinate</term> and a <term><m>y</m>-coordinate</term>.<idx><h sortby="x"><m>x</m>-coordinate</h></idx><idx><h sortby="y"><m>y</m>-coordinate</h></idx> For example, for the point <m>(1,2)\text{,}</m> its <m>x</m>-coordinate is <m>1\text{,}</m> and its <m>y</m>-coordinate is <m>2\text{.}</m> The origin has coordinates <m>(0,0)</m>.</p>

            <p>A Cartesian coordinate system is divided into four <term>quadrants</term>, as shown in <xref ref="figure-quadrants">Figure</xref>.<idx><h>quadrant</h></idx> The quadrants are traditionally labeled with Roman numerals.</p>

            <figure xml:id="figure-quadrants">
                <caption>A Cartesian grid with four quadrants marked</caption>
                <image width="50%">
                    <description>a Cartesian grid with Quadrant I marked in the top right section, Quadrant II marked in the top left section, Quadrant III marked in the bottom left section, Quadrant IV marked in the bottom right section.</description>
                    <latex-image>
                    <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                        \begin{axis}[]
                            \addplot[mark=none] coordinates {(3.5,3.5)} node[] {Quadrant I};
                            \addplot[mark=none] coordinates {(-3.5, 3.5)} node[] {Quadrant II};
                            \addplot[mark=none] coordinates {(-3.5, -3.5)} node[] {Quadrant III};
                            \addplot[mark=none] coordinates {(3.5, -3.5)} node[] {Quadrant IV};
                        \end{axis}
                    \end{tikzpicture}]]>
                    </latex-image>
                </image>
            </figure>
        </statement>
    </definition>

