        <exercisegroup>
            <title>Plotting Points and Choosing a Scale</title>
            <exercise>
                <webwork>
                    <statement>
                        <p>What would be the difficulty with trying to plot <m>(12,4)</m>, <m>(13,5)</m>, and <m>(310,208)</m> all on the same graph?</p>

                        <p><var form="essay" /></p>
                    </statement>
                    <solution>
                        <p>Answers will vary, but the issue is that once you set the scale on both axes so that both <m>(12,4)</m> and <m>(310,208)</m> will appear, then <m>(13,5)</m> will appear to be so close to <m>(12,4)</m> that it will be challenging to draw them both and make it clear they are two different points.</p>
                    </solution>
                </webwork>
            </exercise>
            <exercise>
                <webwork>
                    <statement>
                        <p>The points <m>(3,5)</m>, <m>(5,6)</m>, <m>(7,7)</m>, and <m>(9,8)</m> all lie on a straight line. What can go wrong if you make a plot of a Cartesion plane with these points marked, and you don't have tick marks that are evenly spaced apart?</p>

                        <p><var form="essay" /></p>
                    </statement>
                    <solution>
                        <p>Answers will vary, but the issue is that having irregularly spaced tick marks can make it so that points that are actually in a staright line do not appear to be in a straight line.</p>
                    </solution>
                </webwork>
            </exercise>
